/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.3/claude/bugfix-08-stress-dependency.json:  "response": "## Cycle and the break\n\nThe runtime cycle is:\n\n```\napplication/billing-flow.ts  →  domain/billing.ts  →  presentation/invoice-view.ts  →  application/billing-flow.ts\n```\n\n**Break the `domain → presentation` edge** — remove the `import { renderInvoice }` in `src/domain/billing.ts:2`.\n\n### Why that edge\n\nThree reasons, in priority order:\n\n1. **It's the only edge that's also wrong on its own.** crimes flagged it independently as a `layer_violation` (`domain cannotImport presentation`). The other two edges (`application → domain`, `presentation → application`) are at worst awkward, not architecturally invalid. Cutting this one resolves both findings (`crime_00001` and `crime_00002`) with one change.\n2. **Direction of change.** Domain is supposed to be the stable core; presentation depends on it, not the reverse. `chargeCustomer` calling `renderInvoice` is the inversion — the domain function is producing a rendered string, which is presentation's job.\n3. **Smallest blast radius.** `chargeCustomer` has one call site (`runBillingFlow`). Refactor: domain returns the charge result (e.g. `{ amount }` or just `amount`), and the caller in application — or presentation — formats it. No new shared module needed.\n\n### Minimal fix\n\n```ts\n// src/domain/billing.ts\nexport function chargeCustomer(amount: number): number {\n  return amount; // pure domain — no rendering\n}\n```\n\n```ts\n// src/application/billing-flow.ts — composes domain + presentation\nimport { chargeCustomer } from \"../domain/billing.js\";\nimport { renderInvoice } from \"../presentation/invoice-view.js\";\n\nexport function runBillingFlow(): string {\n  return renderInvoice(chargeCustomer(100));\n}\n```\n\n```ts\n// src/presentation/invoice-view.ts — no longer calls back into application\nexport function renderInvoice(amount: number): string {\n  return `Invoice: ${amount}`;\n}\n```\n\nThat leaves a clean layering: `application → { domain, presentation }`, no cycle, no layer violation. The `deep_import` finding (`crime_00003`) is unrelated and stays — fix separately by using `some-pkg`'s public entry.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.8.1/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3d1b-af9e-73d1-9f44-4f4ca4e34297\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: `src/billing.ts` reads wall-clock time directly inside billing logic.\\n\\nThe key finding is:\\n\\n`crime_00009` / `direct_date` in `src/billing.ts`\\n- 5 uses of `Date.now()`\\n- 2 uses of `new Date()`\\n- lines `57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273`\\n\\nFor a date-boundary billing test, that is the strongest explanation for flakiness. If invoice generation, billing periods, due dates, grace windows, or proration logic call `Date.now()` multiple times during one run, the result can change depending on when the test executes. Around midnight, month-end, year-end, timezone boundaries, or DST transitions, two clock reads in the same function can fall into different calendar buckets.\\n\\nThe large `generateInvoice` function makes this worse: `crime_00002` says it is 204 lines long, so date reads are likely spread across multiple responsibilities. A test may freeze or assume one “current” moment, while the implementation observes several.\\n\\nProposed fix: inject a clock into billing code and capture “now” once per operation.\\n\\nExample shape:\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: InvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // use `now` throughout invoice generation\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen tests can pass a fixed boundary date:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-01-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\nconst invoice = generateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n```\\n\\nI would also make all billing date calculations use UTC consistently, especially if the failing case is month/day boundary related. The scan also reports mixed UTC/local date handling in `src/date.ts`, so billing should avoid local `getMonth()`, `getDate()`, etc. unless the business rule explicitly depends on the customer’s locale/timezone.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":29264,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":461,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":24}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.3/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3925-1ab1-7721-99b5-ae9ec3cc6fb6\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: `crime_00004` / `direct_date` in [src/billing.ts](src/billing.ts). The billing path reads wall-clock time directly in `generateInvoice` (`Date.now()` / `new Date()` on lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250) and elsewhere around line 273. That is exactly the kind of risk factor that creates date-boundary flakes: one branch may calculate period start/end, due dates, proration, or invoice timestamps using slightly different “now” values if the test runs across midnight, month-end, DST, or timezone boundaries.\\n\\nSecondary risk: `generateInvoice` is a 204-line god function, so the date logic is probably mixed with invoice construction, discounts, reminders, and status handling. That makes it easy for one hidden `Date.now()` to survive even if a test pins another date input.\\n\\nProposed fix: inject a single clock value into billing logic and derive all invoice dates from that one instant.\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: GenerateInvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // use `now` everywhere in this invoice calculation\\n  // avoid Date.now() / new Date() inside the function body\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen update tests to pass a fixed clock:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-01-31T12:00:00.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\nconst invoice = generateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n```\\n\\nThe important part is not just “mock Date”; it is making `generateInvoice` observe time once, explicitly. That removes the date-boundary race and gives tests a stable fixture for month-end/timezone cases.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":24636,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":431,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":40}}\n",
