/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.8.1/claude/review-02-react-dashboard.json:  "response": "# Triage by detector\n\n**Read-the-room caveat first:** the paths announce this is the Next.js `learn` tutorial — `basics/*-starter` ↔ `basics/*-final` and `dashboard/starter-example` ↔ `dashboard/final-example` are *pedagogical* pairs, not accidental duplication. That context flips most of the duplicate findings from \"real\" to \"false positive in this repo.\" I've noted that explicitly where it applies.\n\n---\n\n## `exact_duplicate_block` — 46 findings · medium · agent_risk 0.62\n**Verdict: ignore (with one warn)**\n\nThese are entirely starter↔final or basics tutorial-step duplicates. The whole point of the fixture is that each step has its own snapshot. Extracting a shared helper would defeat the purpose.\n\n- The lone *intra*-suite case worth flagging: `crime_00002`, `crime_00003`, `crime_00004` show `getSortedPostsData` / its inner block / `getAllPostIds` across **5** sibling `basics/*` directories. If this weren't a tutorial, that 5× copy with `confidence 0.95` and `agent_risk 0.62` would be a clear **warn** — extract-to-shared-lib territory. In context: **ignore**.\n- Everything else is pairwise final/starter — agent_risk is high purely because the detector can't see that these directories are not meant to converge. Categorical **ignore**.\n\n## `commented_out_code` — 9 findings · severity mixed · agent_risk 0.49–0.61\n**Verdict: warn (medium ones), ignore (low ones)**\n\nThis is the cleanest category. Severity tracks line count and code-density of the corpse.\n\n- **Warn** (medium, agent_risk 0.61): `crime_00047` (`route.ts` with `try/catch/await/return`), `crime_00048` (38 lines of disabled JSX in `latest-invoices.tsx`), `crime_00049` (30 lines in `revenue-chart.tsx`), `crime_00050` (34 lines in `pagination.tsx`). These are exactly the snippets that mislead agents into reviving the \"old way.\" Reviewer should ask \"delete or document why\" before merge.\n- **Ignore** (low, agent_risk ≤ 0.51): the 5 short ones are mostly 2-line `console.log` blocks or tutorial scaffolding (`crime_00070`–`crime_00073`, `crime_00088`, `crime_00089`). Low signal, blocking on these is theatre.\n\n## `magic_domain_literal_scatter` — 1 finding · medium · agent_risk 0.60\n**Verdict: warn**\n\n`crime_00051` — `\"status\"` literal across 5 production files (`actions.ts`, `create-form.tsx`, `edit-form.tsx` × 2). Medium severity + 0.60 agent_risk is the detector saying *this string is a policy in disguise*. Won't break the PR, but a reviewer should ask \"is there an `InvoiceStatus` enum somewhere?\" before approving the next feature that touches it.\n\n## `duplicated_role_status_plan_check` — 2 findings · medium · agent_risk 0.57\n**Verdict: warn**\n\n`crime_00053` (`\"pending\"`) and `crime_00054` (`\"paid\"`) — same literal compared in 4 files with **2 distinct expression shapes**. That divergence is the wedge: `invoice.status === \"pending\"` vs `status === \"pending\"` are easy to update in one place and miss in the other. Worth flagging as a \"future-you problem\" even in tutorial code; if this fixture were real product code, this is the canonical agent-risk smell.\n\n## `duplicate_component_shape` — 1 finding · medium · agent_risk 0.57\n**Verdict: ignore**\n\n`crime_00052` — div subtree shared across `create-form.tsx` ↔ `edit-form.tsx` × {starter, final}. Same tutorial-pair issue as `exact_duplicate_block`; the structural pair is by design. Categorical **ignore**.\n\n## `sync_io_in_hotpath` — 6 findings · low · agent_risk 0.51\n**Verdict: ignore**\n\n`crime_00061`–`crime_00066` — `fs.readdirSync` / `fs.readFileSync` inside `getSortedPostsData` in tutorial `lib/posts.js`. These run inside `getStaticProps` / build-time data fetching, where sync I/O is actually idiomatic Next.js. The detector is mechanically correct but contextually fine. Low severity is exactly the right ladder rung; reviewer should not block on it.\n\n## `direct_date` — 3 findings · low · agent_risk 0.51\n**Verdict: warn**\n\n`crime_00067` (`actions.ts:57` minting `new Date()` to write an invoice date) is the one with bite — server action writing wall time straight into the DB is a real determinism problem the moment someone adds tests. `crime_00068`/`crime_00069` (`utils.ts:14`, generating a date label in `formatDateToLocal`) are presentation-layer and benign. Flag once, don't block.\n\n## `oversized_raster` — 5 findings · low · agent_risk 0.52\n**Verdict: ignore**\n\n`hero-desktop.png` at 486 KB and `opengraph-image.png` at 237 KB are heavy, but they're hero/OG images — exactly the slots where a single resize/AVIF re-encode would help, but not merge-blocking. Low severity is correct; treat as a follow-up.\n\n## `raster_should_be_vector` — 12 findings · low · agent_risk 0.50\n**Verdict: ignore (false-positive prone)**\n\n`crime_00074`–`crime_00085` — all are 56–60 px customer avatar PNGs (`amy-burns.png`, `lee-robinson.png`, …). Avatars aren't logos; they're photographic crops at icon size, where SVG would *not* be the right format. Detector reasoning is the right shape but the wrong call here. Don't block; consider tightening detector heuristics to filter photographic content.\n\n## `deep_import` — 2 findings · low · agent_risk 0.50\n**Verdict: warn**\n\n`crime_00086`/`crime_00087` — both import `react-syntax-highlighter/dist/cjs/styles/prism`. The package doesn't expose its styles on its public surface, so this deep import is partially forced. Real risk: silent break on package upgrade. Worth a note so future agents don't blindly bump the dep version.\n\n## `design_token_escape` — 8 findings · low · agent_risk 0.48\n**Verdict: ignore**\n\n`crime_00090`–`crime_00097` — hard-coded `px` values (18px, 14px, 9px) in form/skeleton/login JSX. With no established design-token module in this codebase, \"extract to tokens\" has no target. Low severity + 0.48 agent_risk is exactly right; this is the lowest-priority category in the re