/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.3/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:  "response": "**Most likely cause: `crime_00004` — Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts`.**\n\n`generateInvoice` reads wall time 7 separate times (5× `Date.now()`, 2× `new Date()`) at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273. Across a 204-line function (`crime_00001`, God Function), those calls can straddle a boundary mid-execution — month rollover, DST shift, midnight UTC, year-end. Two reads that the author assumed were \"the same moment\" can land in different periods, producing inconsistent billing windows, prorations, or due dates. That's the classic profile of a test that passes 99% of the time and fails right at the boundary.\n\nThe supporting evidence in the report:\n- `crime_00006` — `\"renders the enterprise plan\"` has zero assertions, so the suite isn't actually pinning behaviour.\n- `crime_00016` — `\"creates an invoice\"` uses only weak matchers.\n- No clock abstraction exists (the same crime fires again in `src/date.ts`, `crime_00005`).\n\nSo tests are weak *and* the code depends on wall time. Flake is inevitable near boundaries.\n\n**Proposed fix (matches the finding's `inject_clock` action):**\n\n1. Introduce a `Clock` seam — `interface Clock { now(): Date }` — with a default `systemClock` and a `fixedClock(date)` for tests.\n2. Take it as a parameter (or module-level injected default) in `generateInvoice`. Replace every `Date.now()` / `new Date()` with **one** `const now = clock.now()` captured at the top of the function, then derive every period/cutoff from that single value. This kills the \"two reads, two moments\" bug class outright.\n3. Do the same refactor in `src/date.ts` so helpers don't sneak wall-time reads back in.\n4. Add a regression test with `fixedClock(new Date(\"2026-01-31T23:59:59.999Z\"))` (and one at a DST transition for the local-time path, if applicable). These are the boundaries the current suite can't express without monkey-patching.\n\nThe God Function and the missing assertions are real but secondary — they explain *why nobody caught this*, not *what's failing*. Fix the clock first; the extraction in `crime_00001` becomes easier once `now` is a single parameter instead of seven scattered reads.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.8.1/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:  "response": "## Most likely cause: Half-UTC, Half-Local on the same Date receiver\n\n**crime_00004** (high) is the smoking gun for a date-boundary flake. In `src/date.ts`, one Date variable `d` is read with `getUTCFullYear()` at L9 *and* `getMonth()` (local) at L41. On a single instant near midnight, these two families disagree by up to a day:\n\n- For a runner in `America/Los_Angeles`, `new Date(\"2026-01-01T03:00:00Z\")` gives `getUTCFullYear() = 2026` but `getMonth() = 11` (December 2025).\n- For a runner in `Asia/Tokyo`, the same instant flips the other way for late-December dates.\n\nThat's exactly the shape of a billing test that passes on the author's laptop, fails in CI, and \"fixes itself\" the next day.\n\n## Compounding factors (all in `src/date.ts`)\n\n- **crime_00010** — `new Date(\"2026-12-20\")` and `new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")` (L29, L33) have no timezone marker. Per the ES spec the *date-only* form parses as UTC and the *date-time-without-Z* form parses as **local** — so the two literals don't even agree with each other.\n- **crime_00014** — `+ 86400000` at L52 silently drops/adds an hour across DST.\n- **crime_00003 / crime_00009** — wall-clock reads scattered across `date.ts` (8) and `billing.ts` (7) mean the test can't pin a fixed instant without monkey-patching.\n- **crime_00027** — `toLocaleDateString()` with no locale (L46) makes the rendered output host-dependent on top of the bad math.\n\nThe weak-test findings (crime_00011, 00030) aren't the *cause* — the tests are failing — but they explain why this wasn't caught earlier.\n\n## Fix, in priority order\n\n1. **Pick one Date family per receiver in `src/date.ts`.** For billing/storage, convert L41 to `getUTCMonth()` (and audit the rest of `d`'s reads). This alone likely turns the test green.\n2. **Make the literals explicit.** L29 → `\"2026-12-25T07:00:00Z\"` (or an offset that matches intent); L33 → either keep as `\"2026-12-20\"` knowing it's UTC midnight, or write `\"2026-12-20T00:00:00Z\"` to make it obvious.\n3. **Replace ms day-math at L52** with a calendar-aware `addDays` (Temporal/Luxon/date-fns-tz) so December → January and DST transitions don't drift.\n4. **Inject a clock** into `generateInvoice` and the date helpers so the test can freeze \"now\" instead of relying on the runner's timezone matching the author's.\n\nSteps 1 + 2 are the bug fix; 3 + 4 prevent the next one. The God Function in `billing.ts` (crime_00002, 204 lines) is real but not load-bearing for this failure — defer.",
