1:            const tokens = v.toLowerCase().split(/[^a-z_]+/);\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes/packages/core/src/detectors/action-label-drift.ts:92:            for (const tok of tokens) {\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes/evals/results/0.7.0/claude/refactor-07-stress-frontend.json:2:  \\\"scenario\\\": \\\"refactor-07-stress-frontend\\\",\\n/Users/andrew/dev/crimes/evals/results/0.7.0/claude/refactor-07-stress-frontend.json:7:  \\\"response\\\": \\\"## Refactor proposal for `src/Card.tsx`\\\\n\\\\nA small note on the scan: `crimes context` only surfaces the accessibility finding (`crime_00001`). The design-token escape and responsive fragility are visible in the source (and in the file's own header comment), but no detector keyed to those exists yet — so the refactor addresses all three issues the file was built to demonstrate, even though only one shows up in `findings[]`.\\\\n\\\\n### Proposed `src/Card.tsx`\\\\n\\\\n```tsx\\\\ntype CardProps = {\\\\n  children: React.ReactNode;\\\\n  onActivate?: () => void;\\\\n};\\\\n\\\\nexport function Card({ children, onActivate }: CardProps) {\\\\n  if (onActivate) {\\\\n    return (\\\\n      <button\\\\n        type=\\\\\\\"button\\\\\\\"\\\\n        onClick={onActivate}\\\\n        className=\\\\\\\"w-full max-w-2xl bg-brand-accent text-ink-900\\\\\\\"\\\\n      >\\\\n        {children}\\\\n      </button>\\\\n    );\\\\n  }\\\\n\\\\n  return (\\\\n    <div className=\\\\\\\"w-full max-w-2xl bg-brand-accent text-ink-900\\\\\\\">\\\\n      {children}\\\\n    </div>\\\\n  );\\\\n}\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\n### Each change tied to its finding type\\\\n\\\\n1. **Accessibility (`accessible_interaction_risk`, crime_00001, line 7)** — The `<div onClick>` is replaced with a real `<button type=\\\\\\\"button\\\\\\\">` when the card is interactive, and the click handler is hoisted to an `onActivate` prop. A button is reachable by Tab, activatable by Enter/Space, and announced as a button by screen readers — no `role`/`tabIndex`/`aria-label` workarounds needed. When the card is non-interactive (no `onActivate`), it stays a `<div>` with no click handler at all, which is the safer default than leaving a fake button behind. The suggested action in the finding (`switch_to_button_or_add_aria`) recommends exactly this swap; preferring the real element over `role=\\\\\\\"button\\\\\\\"` avoids re-implementing keyboard semantics by hand.\\\\n\\\\n2. **Design-token escape (hex literals in inline `style`)** — `#ff00aa` and `#0a0a0a` are inlined hex values that bypass the design system: they can't be themed, can't be audited for contrast, and won't track palette changes. They're replaced with Tailwind utility classes that resolve to named tokens (`bg-brand-accent`, `text-ink-900`). The exact token names depend on the project's `tailwind.config.*`; if those keys don't exist yet, add them there rather than re-inlining hex. Inline `style` is also dropped entirely, which removes the per-render style object allocation as a small bonus.\\\\n\\\\n3. **Responsive fragility (fixed `width: 800`)** — A hard-coded 800px width overflows any viewport under 800px and refuses to grow on larger ones. It's replaced with `w-full max-w-2xl` so the card fills its container by default and caps at roughly the same visual width on wide screens (`max-w-2xl` ≈ 672px; pick `max-w-3xl` or define a custom `max-w-card` token if you want closer to 800). This makes the component work inside any layout slot without the parent having to clamp it.\\\\n\\\\n### Suggested follow-ups (out of scope for this fixture but worth flagging)\\\\n\\\\n- Add a snapshot/RTL test that asserts the rendered element is a `<button>` when `onActivate` is provided — this would close the `test_gap: 1.00` score on the existing finding.\\\\n- If you want the design-token escape and fixed-pixel-width to actually show up in future scans, those would be new detectors in `packages/language-js` (e.g. `style_token_escape`, `fixed_pixel_layout`) feeding into `core`'s finding schema — the