/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.15/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3cc8-03cb-7692-a072-3f69ab40a16d\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: billing code reads wall time directly and probably crosses a date boundary during the test.\\n\\nThe strongest findings are:\\n\\n- `src/billing.ts` has 7 direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls, including inside `generateInvoice`.\\n- `src/date.ts` mixes UTC and local methods on the same `Date` receiver: `getUTCFullYear()` with `getMonth()`.\\n- `src/date.ts` also has timezone-unsafe parses and DST-naive day math.\\n\\nFor a date-boundary flaky billing test, the likely failure mode is: invoice generation observes “now” multiple times, or formats/computes billing dates partly in UTC and partly in local time. Around midnight, DST, or when CI runs in a different timezone, the invoice period/due date can shift by one day or month.\\n\\nProposed fix:\\n\\n1. Inject a clock into billing code instead of calling `Date.now()` / `new Date()` directly.\\n2. Capture `now` once at the top of `generateInvoice`.\\n3. Use one date family consistently, preferably UTC for billing/domain logic.\\n4. Add a regression test pinned to a boundary instant, for example `2026-03-01T00:00:00.000Z` or a DST transition case.\\n\\nExample shape:\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: InvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // derive all billing dates from `now`\\n  // use getUTCFullYear(), getUTCMonth(), getUTCDate(), etc.\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen in tests:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-03-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\nconst invoice = generateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n\\nexpect(invoice.periodStart).toBe(\\\"2026-03-01\\\");\\n```\\n\\nI would fix `src/billing.ts` first by removing repeated wall-clock reads, then audit the date helper for the UTC/local mix because that is the most likely source of off-by-one date behavior across machines.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":29264,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":533,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":74}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.0/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e377b-df1b-73b1-8476-76917e0854fe\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: `crime_00004` / `direct_date` in [src/billing.ts](src/billing.ts), especially because the failure is date-boundary-related.\\n\\nThe scan says `billing.ts` reads wall time directly in 7 places: `Date.now()` and `new Date()` on lines `57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273`. That makes tests depend on the exact instant they run. Around midnight, month end, trial expiry, invoice cutoff, or timezone boundaries, two calls made milliseconds apart can land on different logical billing days.\\n\\nProposed fix: inject a clock into the billing code and use one captured `now` value per operation.\\n\\nExample shape:\\n\\n```ts\\nexport type Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nexport const systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n```\\n\\nThen billing functions should accept a clock, defaulting to `systemClock`:\\n\\n```ts\\nexport function createInvoice(input: InvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // use `now` everywhere in this operation\\n}\\n```\\n\\nTests can then pin the boundary:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-01-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\ncreateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n```\\n\\nI would fix this before chasing the weaker test findings. The weak tests explain why the bug escaped; the direct clock reads are the likely source of the flakiness.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":24630,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":346,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":22}}\n",
